      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm running a linear regression on some housing price data and the residuals don't look normal at all. the distribution is pretty skewed. what's the best way to handle this if i want to keep using a linear model?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A skewed residual distribution, a classic problem, is often best tackled by transforming your data. You can try a log transformation on the dependent variable (the housing price) or perhaps a square root transformation, depending on how the skew is behaving. It's a good first step, though sometimes you need to check if the issue is with the model assumptions themselves, not just the noise. Remember, even the best-looking data can be undermined by a poorly-chosen variable.",
