    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "winsorization sounds okay but i'm worried about the scale. these outliers are so far outside the normal range that it feels like they might be totally different types of observations rather than just extreme normal cases. how do i tell if they're actually errors or just really high-value properties that follow a different logic?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If those outliers feel like they belong to a different kind of observation, you might be looking at a structural break or a separate population, not just noise. Before you start trimming or capping, you should definitely investigate *why* they are so extreme. Look at the original data for those specific points—are they data entry errors, or are they genuinely multi-million dollar mansions that the rest of your dataset doesn't represent?\n\nSometimes, the best approach isn't just a transformation or a cap, but using a more robust model altogether, like a robust linear regression method, which is less sensitive to those heavy hitters. Think of it like this: if a few giant, hairy spiders are crawling around your little pile of moss, you don't just sweep them away; you figure out if they are part of the natural ecosystem or if they are just a giant, misplaced piece of junk.",
      "source": "target",
